column114: I think our communities can benefit from tailored educational materials or events surrounding gender-and-power-based violence in specific communities. All communities exist in their own cultural/social norms that have different lenses of gender roles, expression, and traditions. What can be deconstructed in one community may not function the same in another. It can be examples of gender norms in Hispanic communities compared to Asian communities and how gender/power plays a role in how people interact, and interpret what is okay and what is harmful. There is an overarching consensus of what is morally right and wrong, but if different communities are educated in different ways, they may not always understand that certain norms cause harm. These resources can include dialogues and discussions between students or articles highlighting different points of views from students about their experiences that can then be shared through a newsletter or panel.
column115: It’s important to have dialogue between students, especially a diverse group of students from different backgrounds. So whether it’s a social event or a workshop, being able to talk to other students and share experiences is helpful in understanding our own experiences as well as what other members of our communities experience. Maybe having specific topics that come up consistently in certain cultures (e.g. machismo in Latinx culture and gender based violence) that can be turned into discussions or a workshop that helps deconstruct harmful messaging or identify the behavior.
